Section 4: Validation Results — Statistical Methods

1. Overview

Section 4.1 provides the definitive CytoSig vs SecAct summary across 6 datasets. Four method rows per dataset:

  •  CytoSig  — all 43 cytokine signatures (33–43 passing filters per dataset)
  •  CytoSig (matched)  — restricted to the 32 targets shared with SecAct
  •  SecAct  — all 1,170 secreted protein signatures (805–1,161 passing filters)
  •  SecAct (matched)  — restricted to the 32 targets shared with CytoSig

Statistical tests: Total comparisons use Mann–Whitney U (unpaired, unequal n); matched comparisons use Wilcoxon signed-rank (paired by target via alias resolution). All p-values are BH–FDR corrected within each figure.

2. Independence-Corrected Methodology

All correlations use a median-of-medians approach to ensure statistical independence:

  • GTEx (by_tissue): median across 29 tissues. TCGA (primary_by_cancer): median across 33 cancer types.
  • CIMA, Inflammation Atlas Main, scAtlas Normal/Cancer: one ρ per target at donor/tumor level (no aggregation needed).

% Sig: BH-FDR (q < 0.05) within each dataset × method group.

6. Cross-Dataset Comparison: Statistical Methods

Section 4.2 of the interactive report compares the Spearman ρ distributions of CytoSig and SecAct across 6 independent atlases using independence-corrected statistics. For GTEx (29 tissues) and TCGA (33 cancer types), each target’s representative ρ is the median across per-tissue/per-cancer values (median-of-medians). For donor-only datasets (CIMA, Inflammation Main, scAtlas Normal/Cancer), each target already has one ρ. Two complementary statistical tests are used, corresponding to the two tabs in the interactive figure.

Total Comparison (Mann–Whitney U Test)

The Mann–Whitney U test (Wilcoxon rank-sum) is a non-parametric test comparing two independent samples, testing whether one distribution is stochastically greater than the other. This test is appropriate because CytoSig and SecAct measure different sets of proteins with unequal sample sizes (~43 vs ~1,170), and the ρ distributions are not necessarily normal.

Procedure:

  1. For GTEx/TCGA: compute the median ρ across tissues/cancers per target (excluding “all” and “unmappable” strata). For CIMA, Inflammation Main, scAtlas: use the direct independent-level ρ.
  2. Collect representative ρ values for all CytoSig targets and all SecAct targets per atlas.
  3. Apply two-sided Mann–Whitney U test (scipy.stats.mannwhitneyu, alternative='two-sided').
  4. Apply BH–FDR correction across 6 atlases.
AtlasnCSnSAU statisticprawqBHSig.
GTEx431,13216,705.04.76 × 10−49.51 × 10−4***
TCGA411,08516,142.02.85 × 10−34.27 × 10−3**

Inflammation Main3380514,101.05.48 × 10−15.48 × 10−1ns

scAtlas (Cancer)431,14014,822.01.06 × 10−56.36 × 10−5***

Matched Comparison (Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test)

The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is a non-parametric paired test on the 32 shared targets (22 direct + 10 alias-resolved). Each shared target serves as its own control — one ρ from CytoSig and one from SecAct for the same cytokine. TCGA has 30 pairs (IFNL1/IL36A absent); Inflammation Main has 27 pairs (smaller target set).

Alias resolution (10 pairs): Activin A→INHBA, CD40L→CD40LG, GCSF→CSF3, GMCSF→CSF2, IFNL→IFNL1, IL36→IL36A, MCSF→CSF1, TNFA→TNF, TRAIL→TNFSF10, TWEAK→TNFSF12

Procedure:

  1. Collect the Spearman ρ for each shared target in both CytoSig and SecAct, using alias resolution to match names.
  2. Compute paired differences: Δi = ρSecAct,i − ρCytoSig,i.
  3. Apply two-sided Wilcoxon signed-rank test (scipy.stats.wilcoxon) on non-zero differences.
  4. Apply BH–FDR correction across 6 atlases.

Independence Correction Notes

  • GTEx: Each target’s representative ρ = median across 29 tissues (median-of-medians). nCytoSig = 43 targets (not 43 × 29 = 1,247 tissue-target pairs).
  • TCGA: Each target’s representative ρ = median across 33 cancer types. nCytoSig = 41 targets.
  • CIMA: One ρ per target at donor_only level. nCytoSig = 43.
  • Inflammation Main: One ρ per target at donor_only level. nCytoSig = 33 (smaller target set).
  • scAtlas Normal/Cancer: One ρ per target at donor_only/tumor_only level. n = 43 CytoSig, 1,140 SecAct.

8. Cross-Platform Comparison: Statistical Methods

Section 4.4 of the interactive report compares per-target Spearman ρ values between bulk RNA-seq (GTEx/TCGA) and single-cell pseudobulk (scAtlas) for matching tissues/cancer types. The question is whether per-target ρ values differ systematically between measurement platforms.

Test Design

The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is used because the comparison is paired by target: each target has one ρ from the bulk platform and one from pseudobulk, computed on the same tissue/cancer type. This yields a paired difference for each target, testing whether the median difference is zero. A minimum of 6 paired targets is required.

Procedure per stratum (tissue or cancer type):

  1. Merge bulk and single-cell DataFrames on target name to obtain paired ρ values.
  2. Apply two-sided Wilcoxon signed-rank test (scipy.stats.wilcoxon, alternative='two-sided').
  3. Apply BH–FDR correction across all strata within each comparison, separately per signature (CytoSig and SecAct corrected independently).

Caveats

Several factors may contribute to platform differences: (1) different sample sizes per tissue (GTEx 47–3,234 vs scAtlas 10–124), (2) different gene sets (GTEx ~56K vs scAtlas ~22K genes), (3) bulk vs pseudobulk composition (true bulk includes all cell types vs pseudobulk summed from annotated cells), (4) different donor demographics (GTEx post-mortem vs scAtlas surgical/biopsy), and (5) normalization differences (TPM vs pseudobulk counts). CytoSig’s smaller target set (~40 targets) has limited power per stratum, while SecAct’s ~1,000+ paired targets provide high power, explaining why SecAct detects more significant cross-platform differences.

9. Effect of Aggregation Level: Statistical Methods

Section 4.6 of the interactive report examines how the CytoSig vs SecAct comparison changes across aggregation levels. The same Mann–Whitney U (total) and Wilcoxon signed-rank (matched) tests are applied at each aggregation level within each atlas. BH–FDR correction is applied across levels within each atlas.

How ρ values are generated at each level

At each aggregation level, pseudobulk expression profiles are computed by averaging single-cell data within each group (e.g., donor × cell type). At coarser levels, each target has one ρ per donor grouping. At finer levels, each target contributes multiple ρ values (one per donor × cell-type combination), increasing sample size but reducing cells per pseudobulk group.

Total Comparison: inflated n at finer levels

At finer levels, the Total comparison n grows substantially (e.g., CIMA: 43 → 2,914 for CytoSig across 5 levels). These observations are not independent across cell types within the same target, which inflates significance. The extremely small p-values at fine levels should be interpreted cautiously.

Matched Comparison: median-aggregate before pairing

At finer levels, each target produces multiple ρ values (e.g., 7 cell types in CIMA L1). These within-target observations are not independent. To meet the Wilcoxon test’s independence assumption, we take the median per target first, yielding one representative ρ per target (32 pairs), then apply the paired test.
